  "prompt": "What is the difference between a possum and an opossum?",
  "response": "The terms \"possum\" and \"opossum\" refer to different groups of marsupials, and the primary distinctions are related to their species and geographic distribution.\n\n1. **Opossum**:\n   - The term \"opossum\" specifically refers to the Virginia opossum (*Didelphis virginiana*), which is the only marsupial found in North America. \n   - Opossums are known for their ability to play dead as a defense mechanism and have a distinctive appearance with a hairless tail and pointed face.\n\n2. **Possum**:\n   - The term \"possum\" generally refers to various species of marsupials found primarily in Australia and nearby regions, which belong to different families, such as the suborder Phalangeriformes. \n   - Common examples include the common brushtail possum (*Trichosurus vulpecula*) and the sugar glider (*Petaurus breviceps*).\n   - Possums typically have fur-covered tails and a somewhat different body shape compared to opossums.\n\nIn summary, while the \"opossum\" (with the 'o') usually refers to the North American species, \"possum\" (without the 'o') refers to a wider variety of similar marsupials found in Australia and nearby areas.",
